Preheat your oven to 180°C and bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with
@salt{1/2%tsp}. Halve the @cherry tomatoes{1%package}. Place on a #baking tray{},
drizzle with @olive oil{} and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Toss, spread
out in a single layer, roast on the top shelf of your oven until soft,
~{15%minutes}. We will add it to the sauce later. Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly
slice the @echalion shallot{1}(peeled and thinly sliced).

Heat a splash of @olive oil{2%tsp} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Fry the
@British smoked bacon lardons{90%g} until crispy, ~{3-4%minutes}. Stir in the
shallot and cook until soft, ~{3-4%minutes}, stirring regularly. Add the
@chopped tomatoes with basil{1%tin}, @smoked paprika{1%tsp} and
@chicken stock powder{1}. Stir to dissolve, lower the heat and simmer gently until
the sauce is nice and thick, ~{10-12%minutes}. > Add a splash of water if the sauce
looks a little dry. Add the roasted tomatoes to the sauce once it's ready.

Meanwhile, add the @penne pasta{200%g} to your pan of boiling water and cook until
tender, ~{12%minutes}.

While the pasta cooks, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or
use a #garlic press{}) and mix with the @olive oil{2%tbsp}. Season with @salt{}.
Halve the @ciabatta{1} length ways (as if you were making a sandwich) and spoon or
brush the garlic oil across the cut sides of the ciabatta. Sprinkle over half the
@grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g} then pop on the baking tray you used for
the pepper. Bake on the top shelf of your oven until golden, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Meanwhile, roughly chop the @chives{1}(roughly chopped) (or use #scissors{} if that's
easier). When the pasta is cooked, drain it in a #colander{} and stir it into your
thickened tomato sauce. Stir in half the chives and half the Italian hard cheese
(and another splash of water if you want it to be a bit saucier).

Serve in #bowls{} and sprinkle over the remaining chives. Add a small pinch of
@?chilli flakes{1%pinch} if you like a bit of heat (but be careful they're hot!).
Slice the ciabatta diagonally into triangles and serve alongside. Enjoy!

> When you can get your kids to eat more veg without the teatime tantrums, you know
> you've found a recipe worth holding on to. Once you've served the kids, turn up the
> heat by making this dish into an arrabbiata by adding crushed chilli flakes. Buon
> appetito!